[[Lieutenant General]] '''Andrew Gordon''' (died 17 April 1806) was a [[British Army]] officer who became [[Lieutenant Governor of Jersey]].

==Military career==
Born in [[Scotland]], Gordon became a [[major]] in the [[26th (Cameronian) Regiment of Foot|26th Regiment of Foot]] in 1777.<ref name=reg>[http://www.napoleon-series.org/military/organization/Britain/Infantry/Regiments/c_26thFoot.html British Regiments and the Men Who Led Them 1793-1815: 26th Regiment of Foot]</ref> He was promoted to [[lieutenant-colonel]] in 1784, [[colonel]] in 1790,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13258|startpage=705|date=20 November 1794|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> [[major-general]] in 1794,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=131710|startpage=1011|date=4 October 1794|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> and [[lieutenant-general]]  in 1801 (from brevet, 1799).<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15326|startpage=37|date= 6 January 1801|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> He was appointed [[Lieutenant Governor of Jersey]] in 1797<ref name=reg/><ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13994|supp=|startpage=273|date=21 March 1797|accessdate=22 May 2011}}</ref> and died in office in 1806.<ref name=reg/>

He was also Colonel of the [[89th (The Princess Victoria's) Regiment of Foot]] from 1795 to 1797, the [[59th (2nd Nottinghamshire) Regiment of Foot|59th Regiment of Foot]] from 1797 to 1801 and Colonel of the [[26th (Cameronian) Regiment of Foot|26th Regiment of Foot]] from 1801 to his death in 1806.<ref name=reg/>

